      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented V&V test suite, version control, and change management procedures consistent with MRL 5 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is used with documented QA procedures, regression test suite, and ISO 9001-compliant change management. Software quality assurance achieved at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through benchmark problems with known analytical solutions.",
      "rationale": "Solver benchmarked against Taylor-Couette flow and lid-driven cavity analytical solutions. Observed order of accuracy consistent with second-order spatial discretization. Code verification achieved at required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) must be computed using Richardson extrapolation on three systematically refined meshes. GCI for hemolysis QoI must be below 5%.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh levels (3.2M, 9.6M, 28.8M cells) evaluated. GCI for normalized index of hemolysis is 3.1% on the fine mesh. Discretization error is well-characterized and within acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must match COU operating conditions within specified tolerances for flow rate, rotational speed, and fluid properties.",
      "rationale": "In-vitro experiments conducted at 2500 and 3500 RPM, 3–7 L/min flow, using bovine blood at 37°C. Operating conditions replicate VAD COU envelope. Temperature and viscosity controlled within ±2% of target values."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., RMSE, bias, validation uncertainty) must be computed for primary QoI. Model must fall within combined experimental and numerical uncertainty at 95% confidence.",
      "rationale": "Validation uncertainty computed per ASME V&V 20. At four of five operating points, CFD predictions fall within the 95% confidence interval of experimental NIH measurements. Systematic bias of +4.2% identified at highest flow condition and documented."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI used in validation (NIH) must be directly linked to the clinical decision metric (absolute hemolysis threshold) with documented mapping.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the regulatory-accepted surrogate for hemolysis risk in VAD submissions. Direct mapping from NIH to clinical hemolysis threshold documented per ASTM F1841. QoI relevance confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must cover the full COU operating envelope. Geometry, boundary conditions, and fluid properties in validation experiments must match COU device and conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the reference geometry for the COU. All five COU operating points are included in the validation dataset. Relevance to COU is high."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated with residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations. Round-off and iterative errors must be shown to be negligible relative to discretization error.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and turbulence equations. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout. Iterative error estimated at less than 0.1% of GCI-estimated discretization error."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup must be reviewed by an independent analyst. Boundary conditions, material properties, and solver settings must be documented and traceable.",
      "rationale": "Independent review of simulation setup performed by a senior CFD engineer not involved in original model construction. All boundary conditions and solver settings documented in a traceable simulation data package."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection must be justified for rotating machinery hemolysis prediction. Model form uncertainty must be estimated by comparing at least two turbulence closure approaches.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega and realizable k-epsilon turbulence models compared across all operating points. NIH predictions differ by 6–9% between models, with SST k-omega showing better agreement with PIV data. Model form uncertainty quantified and included in total uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Distributions must be assigned to uncertain input parameters. Monte Carlo propagation must be performed with sufficient samples to characterize output uncertainty. A screening sensitivity study is noted in the UQ report to identify influential inputs.",
      "rationale": "Monte Carlo UQ performed with 500 Latin hypercube samples propagated through the hemolysis power-law model. Input distributions assigned to blood viscosity, power-law exponents, and rotational speed tolerance. The UQ report narrative references a preliminary screening sensitivity study identifying viscosity and power-law coefficient C as potentially influential; however, this screening was conducted informally and its results are described qualitatively in the report appendix rather than encoded as a structured sensitivity analysis record. Input uncertainty contributes ±12% to predicted NIH at the 95th percentile."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental samples used in validation must be representative of the COU population. Sample size must be sufficient to estimate experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Six independent blood loop experiments performed at each of five operating points (n=30 total). Bovine blood from three different donors used to capture biological variability. Sample size sufficient for 95% confidence interval estimation per ASTM F1841 guidance."
    },
